==English==

===Etymology===
From Ancient Greek '''[[δαίμων]]''' (daimōn) ‘god, goddess, divine power, genius, guardian spirit’, from '''[[δαίω]]''' (daiō) ‘to divide, to distribute destinies, to allot’.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/'di:mən/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# an [[evil]] [[spirit]]
# a fallen [[angel]] or Satanic divinity; a false [[god]]
# one's inner [[spirit]] or [[genius]], a [[daimon]]
# (''Greek mythology'') a [[spirit]] or lesser divinity between [[men]] and [[god]]s
# a [[foible]]; a [[flaw]] in a person's [[character]]
#:''The demon of stupidity haunts me whenever I open my mouth.''
# someone of remarkable or diabolical [[energy]] or [[ability]]
#:''He's a demon at the card tables.''

====Alternative spellings====
*[[daemon]], [[d&aelig;mon]] ''(these spellings are generally only found for the senses of '''inner spirit''' and '''divinity of Greek mythology''')''

